8.1.5 Conclusion¶

The busiest days of the week for orders are 0 and 1, that is Saturday and Sunday. There are much fewer orders during the week.

The busiest hours of the day are between 9.00-16.00. Orders grow until around 10.00, dip slightly at 12.00 (presumably when users have lunch), rise slightly again until 14.00 and begins to decline thereafter.

Essentially it demonstrates a bell curve, but with the expected peak truncated somewhat for lunch at 12-13.00.

There is no significant difference when filtering profiles, except for there are slightly fewer orders on a Sunday from the significant profiles.

8.4 Customer behaviour: how often do customers return to Instacart?¶

8.4.1 How many orders per week do users make?¶

First constructing a histogram for this data returns unusual/unhelpful visualisation. Looking the summary statistics below, we can see why. The vast majority of the statistics are between 0.26 and 0.84, but then there are extreme values, such as 42.

Checking this for errors showed that there are no errors, however for example, user 138747 made their first ever order and then made 5 further orders within the next day. This means he/she made 6 orders in the space of a day, which averages out to 42 orders a week.

Since this is unhelpful for our analysis, we will exclude users that fit the mean +- 2 standard deviations outlier rule (users with weekly_orders outside the range 0-1.725526 will be excluded).

8.4.3 Conclusion¶

There are two ways here to consider usage frequency.

By considering the number of orders that users make per week:

  • The mean number of orders made per week is 0.7.
  • There are very few users who make fewer orders than this and the number of users who make more orders than this gradually decline to about 1.7 orders per week.

By considering the number of weeks until users make their next order:

  • On average, users make their next order after 1.75 weeks and the majority of users make their next order within 1-2.5 weeks.

8.5 Customer behaviour: are there differences in ordering habits based on a customer’s loyalty status?¶

What does the client consider to be loyal?

Frequency of orders? May not represent amount spent

# Conduct t-test on the upper extreme weekly_spending mean (West)

# Let's first filter the DataFrame to get the data for the West region
data = df_spend[df_spend['region'] == 'West']['weekly_spending']

# Now, calculate the mean and standard deviation for the West region data
mean = data.mean()
std = data.std()

# Calculate the mean and standard deviation for the entire dataset
overall_mean = df_spend['weekly_spending'].mean()
overall_std = df_spend['weekly_spending'].std()

# Perform the two-sample t-test
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(data, df_spend['weekly_spending'], equal_var=False)

# Print the results
print(f"West Region Mean: {mean:.2f}")
print(f"Overall Mean: {overall_mean:.2f}")
print(f"t-statistic: {t_stat:.2f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value:.5f}")

# Check if the p-value is less than the significance level (e.g., 0.05) to determine significance
alpha = 0.05
if p_value < alpha:
    print("The mean weekly spending for the West region is significantly different from the overall mean.")
else:
    print("There is no significant difference in the mean weekly spending for the West region.")

P-value: 0.29671
There is no significant difference in the mean weekly spending for the West region.

9 Analysis Conclusion & Summary¶

9.1 General Spending¶

Total Spending

  • Minimum: 5.00
  • Mean: 1483.35
  • Max: 26,394.90

Average Weekly Spending Per Customer

  • Minimum: 0.37
  • Mean: 54.89
  • Max: 2761.94

Average Orders Per Week Per Customer

  • Minimum: 0.26
  • Mean: 0.71
  • Max: 42

The greatest income is from the South, followed by the West and Midwest (with similar income) and the Northeast with lowest income. This follows the general US population trends by region.

See section 7.2.2 for more details.

9.2 Busiest days of the week and hours of the day¶

The busiest days of the week for orders are Saturday and Sunday. There are much fewer orders during the week.

The busiest hours of the day are between 9.00-16.00. Orders grow until around 10.00, dip slightly at 12.00 (presumably when users have lunch), rise slightly again until 14.00 and begins to decline thereafter.

Essentially it demonstrates a bell curve, but with the expected peak truncated somewhat for lunch at 12-13.00.

There is no significant difference when filtering profiles, except for there are slightly fewer orders on a Sunday from the significant profiles.

See sections 8.1 and 8.2 for more detail.

9.3 Profiling¶

Customers have been profiled as one of the following and so that no one customer has more than one profile type: Specialist profiles

  • Health Families
  • Grocery Enthusiasts
  • Simple Pleasures
  • Young Spender
  • Frugal DIY

Non-Specialist profiles

  • Professional
  • Family
  • Budget
  • Senior

The vast majority of customers can be profiled as Families, Healthy Families and Professionals. These profile were henceforth referred to as "significant profiles" in the analysis. The distribution of customer profiles across different regions is much the same and there are more of each in the South and less in the Northeast. This is not unusual and meets expectations, as it follows the general US population distribution by region.

See section 6.7 for more details.

9.4 Best selling products¶

The standout, best selling product departments are produce and dairy, followed by snacks and beverages. This indicates a general profile for Instacart customers of healthy shopping and eating, which correlates with the Healthy Families profile being one of the most significant profiles. The spending habits across regions are not different, that is each region has the same distribution of sales by department. Raw sales are different, but this is accounted for by differing amounts of customers per region, following the population distribution of the US. Of the 10 best selling products, 9 are produce (mostly fruit) and 1 is a dairy product.

See section 8.3 for more details.

9.5 How often customers return to Instacart¶

As per the requirements of the project, all customers with fewer than 5 orders were excluded from the analysis.

There are two ways here to consider usage frequency.

By considering the number of orders that users make per week:

  • The mean number of orders made per week is 0.7.
  • There are very few users who make fewer orders than this and the number of users who make more orders than this gradually decline to about 1.7 orders per week.

By considering the number of weeks until users make their next order:

  • On average, users make their next order after 1.75 weeks and the majority of users make their next order within 1-2.5 weeks.

See section 8.4 for more details

9.6 Regional differences in spending habits¶

The pie charts on department sales show that there are no regional differences.

The pie charts show that proportionally the regional, average weekly spending and weekly number of orders are near identical. The t-tests confirm that they are not statistically, significantly different.

There is no significant regional difference in spending habits.

See section 8.6 for more details.

9.7 Differences in spending habits by age and family status¶

Analysis on average number of orders per week and weekly spending by age group and whether the user has dependents showed that: there are no significant differences in spending habits age and family status. T-tests confirmed that the averages of each group were not statistically, significantly different.

Age and family status has no effect on spending habits.

See section 8.7 for more details.
